{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e678a15-9958-4f12-8f36-c498496553b6","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process ID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**To copy it out of the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- Use `--format speedscope` if you want browser-based analysis without Windows tools.\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead — it exposes a `/trace` HTTP endpoint.\n- For a lower-level alternative, `perf record` works too but requires `SYS_ADMIN` / `privileged` and is harder to symbolize.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"841f835b-06f4-4065-9b9f-08d5f526e5e0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I should provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":393,"requestId":"7661:17D0EF:D9928A:FE3BD5:69FE8D8B"},"id":"ba12cd1f-944f-47b7-a499-ce096885123a","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:27:48.778Z","parentId":"eb46e22d-dba8-47c4-9371-dc5097be0f26"}
